Hello all,

I am pleased to announce a new paper titled =E2=80=9CHow transf=
erable are features in deep learning networks.=E2=80=9D It has been accepte=
d at NIPS as an oral presentation, which I=E2=80=99m fired up about because=
 less than 1% of papers were given that honor. A huge congratulations to fi=
rst-author Jason Yosinski on that!

There is no evolution in this paper, bu=
t recently on this list there has been an interest in, and papers about, bo=
th deep learning and transfer learning, so I thought that some of you might=
 find it interesting. One of the co-authors (Yoshua Bengio) also gave a key=
note at this year=E2=80=99s GECCO conference. 

Here is the paper:
J Yosins=
ki, J Clune, Y Bengio, H Lipson (2014) How transferable are features in dee=
p learning networks?. <http://www.evolvingai.org/node/156> Advances in Neur=
al Information Processing Systems 27 (NIPS '14). (pdf <http://www.evolvinga=
i.org/sites/fish34.cs.uwyo.edu.lab/files/2014_YosinskiEtAl_HowTransferableA=
reFeaturesInDNNs_NIPS.pdf>)
As always, I look forward to any comments and o=
r questions you might have. 


Best regards,
Jeff Clune

Assistant Professo=
r, Computer Science
Director, Evolving Artificial Intelligence Lab <http://=
evolvingai.org/>
University of Wyoming
jeffclune@...
jeffclune.com
